Kylie was a normal little girl growing up having fun and doing what kids do, until the fall of 2009. At that time she developed sever abdomial pain and was in and out of every hospital in the area. Finally they removed her galbladder but that did nothing but put her through more trauma. After 1-1/2 yrs the stress of the constant pain not only kept her out of school but she lost several years of her memory. We live a in a small town and good medical help has been hard to find. She was accepted into the Mayo clinic, but our insurance did not have out of state coverage. It's been about 3 years now and she has learned to cope with it but still does not have anything close to a normal life.

I cut a portion of an artical that the local paper did on Kylie when she was "adopted" by the Sparrow Club last year. This is a portion of that article;

Kylie Cross has a favorite quote: "I don't need easy, I just need possible."A little over a year ago, Cross lost most of her short term and childhood memories. She returned to a school where she couldn't remember her friends. She had suffered from a seizure and sustained permanent memory damage. Unfortunately, that's one of many medical problems Kylie has struggled through in her short life. Kylie has gone through far more than the average sophomore at Sisters High School. Instead of worrying about the PSAT or sports practice, she is dealing with Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome, and symptoms such as severe abdominal pain, respiratory issues, hallucinations, and fainting, which doctors have been unable to accurately diagnose. Just six weeks ago she underwent surgery for intestinal bleeding.For Kylie, returning to social life at school after her seizure was "a bit awkward". Without many of her memories and unable to pursue her passion for sports, she felt disconnected...For the full artical, please see: http://www.nuggetnewspaper.com/main.asp?SectionID=8&SubSectionID=8&ArticleID=19613
